===Etymology===
Recorded since the 1340s, as "discharge of semen other than during sex", later, "desecration, defilement" (1382), from Late {{etyl|la|en}} {{l|la|pollutio||defilement}}, from Latin {{l|la|polluere||to soil, defile, contaminate}}, itself from {{l|la|por-||before}} + {{l|la|-luere||to smear}}, related to {{l|la|lutum||mud}} and to {{l|la|lues||filth}}; compare Greek {{l|grc|||filth, dirt, disgrace}} and {{l|grc|||rubbish, refuse}}, Old Irish ''[[loth]]'' "mud, dirt", Lithuanian {{l|lt|lutynas||pool, puddle}}. The meaning "that which makes physically foul" is from 1540s. The sense of "contamination of the environment" was first recorded circa 1860, but not common until circa 1955.

